// 8.335 — 🚨 SOFT-404 fix: /blog/[slug] + /heroes/[cohort] now return real 404 for unknown slugs (was 200-with-not-found-content). Doug 2026-05-08 follow-on grind: caught while verifying new posts render — `curl /blog/nonexistent-test-slug-12345` returned 200 instead of 404. Body contained &ldquo;404&rdquo; + &ldquo;not found&rdquo; text but HTTP status was 200 (Next.js 16 default behavior with `dynamicParams=true` + statically-generated routes). **SEO impact**: Google distinguishes real 404 from soft-404 (200-with-error-content). Soft 404s on `/blog/[slug]` confuse Google about which slugs are real and erode the blog index's authority signal — every WP-era legacy URL that we haven't ported as a real post would have been categorized as soft-404 (Google sees /blog/some-old-slug → 200, content says &ldquo;not found&rdquo;, Google says &ldquo;okay this is a thin/error page on a real URL&rdquo; → de-indexes adjacent paths). Fix: added `export const dynamicParams = false;` to both `/blog/[slug]/page.tsx` + `/heroes/[cohort]/page.tsx` — only slugs from `generateStaticParams()` are served, all others return clean 404 from Next.js's built-in route handler. **Sister fix on glw v7.X parallel ship.** /brands/[slug] LEFT alone — DB-backed dynamic route (brands added via admin, can't be statically locked without breaking new-brand discovery). /deals/[id] LEFT alone — also DB-dynamic. tsc clean. Verification next deploy: `curl -fsS -o /dev/null -w &quot;%{http_code}&quot; /blog/nonexistent-test-slug-12345` should return 404 (was 200).
